    "evidence": "The narrative claimed [Vehicle speed was about 50 km/h when the crash happened.](a1) but telemetry shows GPS speed samples of [98.0 km/h at t=9.0 s, 91.0 km/h at t=10.0 s, 89.0 km/h at t=11.0 s, and 77.0 km/h at t=12.0 s](T4); the compute_stats summary reports a first_value of [102.0 km/h at t=0.0 s] and a last_value of [0.0 km/h at t=16.0 s] with an overall change of [-102.0 km/h](T2). The detected speed drops include a drop from [89.0 km/h to 52.0 km/h between t=11.0 and t=13.0 s](T3), and a later drop from [52.0 km/h to 0.0 km/h between t=13.0 and t=14.0 s](T3), indicating the vehicle was well above 50 km/h at impact times around t\u22489.7\u201310.0 s (near [98.0\u201391.0 km/h](T4))."
   },
   {
    "assertion_id": "a2",
    "verdict": "contradicted",
    "evidence": "The claim \"no significant prior events\" is contradicted by detected pre-impact activity: detect_events found multiple impact spikes and a sustained deceleration window starting at [t=9.63 s with a major spike at t=9.74 s on accel_x of magnitude 5.89 g](T3) and additional spikes at [t=10.03 s and t=10.84 s on accel_x](T3). Also there are large gyro and accel peaks at ~[t=9.74 s](T2) showing significant sudden events rather than no warning."
   },
   {
    "assertion_id": "a3",
    "verdict": "supported",
    "evidence": "The claim that \"The impact was violent\" is supported by high-magnitude sensor peaks: accel_x registered a peak_abs_dev of [5.888 g at t=9.74 s](T2) and detect_events recorded an impact_spike with magnitude [5.89 g at t=9.74 s](T3), and gyro_y showed a peak of [779.491 deg/s at t=9.74 s](T4), indicating a violent crash pulse."
   },
   {
    "assertion_id": "a4",
    "verdict": "supported",
    "evidence": "The assertion that \"The car rotated sharply as a result of the impact\" is supported by strong rotational sensor response: gyro_y peak_abs_dev is [779.318 deg/s with peak_raw_value 779.491 at t=9.74 s](T2) and the downsample shows the same [779.491 deg/s at t=9.74 s](T4), indicating a large rotation-rate spike consistent with a sharp rotation."
   },
   {
    "assertion_id": "a5",
    "verdict": "supported",
    "evidence": "Rotation occurring during or immediately after impact is supported because peak rotational and acceleration activity are co-located: accel and gyro peaks both occur at about [t=9.74 s](T2) (accel_x peak at [t=9.74 s, 5.888 g](T2); gyro_y peak at [t=9.74 s, 779.491 deg/s](T4)), and detect_events marks impact spikes spanning [~9.63\u20139.83 s](T3), consistent with rotation during/immediately after impact before stop."
   },
   {
    "assertion_id": "a6",
    "verdict": "unverifiable",
    "evidence": "The claim \"There was a single collision event\" cannot be decided solely from sensors: detect_events lists multiple impact_spike detections at [t=9.74 s, t=10.06 s, and t=10.84 s on accel channels](T3) and multiple speed-drop segments ([9.0\u201312.0 s], [11.0\u201313.0 s], [13.0\u201314.0 s]) indicating several pulses, but whether these are separate collisions, secondary pulses from one collision, or sensor reflections cannot be determined without additional context (camera or event labeling). Therefore single-event vs multiple is unverifiable."
   }
